<subSubSection id="C31F2DDDBF22FFDC763CF82AF657D43B" pageId="21" pageNumber="432" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BBA7E56BF22FFDC763CF82AF657D43B" blockId="21.[2085,2675,1903,2324]" lastBlockId="21.[1472,2676,2332,3465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="432">
Sufficiently distinct from vulpine foxes to warrant recognition as a separate genus. The Northern Gray Fox often clusters genetically with two other ancient lineages, the Raccoon Dog and the Bat-eared Fox, but the exact relationship is unclear. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0505D5BF22FFDC745BF7EEF784D5C1" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1857" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" genus="Urocyon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="21" pageNumber="432" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Urocyon</taxonomicName>
is currently considered a basal genus within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C0505D5BF22FFDC76D8F75DF6EED5E8" box="[2243,2357,2253,2286]" class="Mammalia" family="Canidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="21" pageNumber="432" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Canidae</taxonomicName>
and has only two surviving members, the Northern Gray Fox and Island Fox (U. lttoralis). Up to sixteen subspecies are recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
